### Dependency Injection Container

Spring's IoC (Inversion of Control) container manages bean creation and wiring. Beans are instantiated and injected automatically based on configuration.

### @Autowired

`@Autowired` tells Spring to inject a bean automatically. It can be applied to constructors, setters, or fields.

### Constructor Injection (Recommended)

Constructor injection is preferred because it makes dependencies explicit, enables immutable fields, and simplifies testing.

```java
@Service
public class UserService {
    private final UserRepository userRepository;
    private final EmailService emailService;

    public UserService(UserRepository userRepository, EmailService emailService) {
        this.userRepository = userRepository;
        this.emailService = emailService;
    }
}
```

### Setter Injection

```java
@Autowired
public void setUserRepository(UserRepository userRepository) {
    this.userRepository = userRepository;
}
```

### Qualifiers
- **@Qualifier**: Resolves ambiguity when multiple beans of the same type exist.
- **@Primary**: Marks a bean as the default when multiple candidates exist.

### Circular Dependency
A circular dependency occurs when Bean A depends on Bean B and Bean B depends on Bean A. To resolve: restructure code, use `@Lazy` on one dependency, or use setter injection.

codeExample:
@Service
public class OrderService {
    private final OrderRepository orderRepository;
    private final InventoryClient inventoryClient;

    public OrderService(OrderRepository orderRepository,
                        @Qualifier("restInventoryClient") InventoryClient inventoryClient) {
        this.orderRepository = orderRepository;
        this.inventoryClient = inventoryClient;
    }
}
